13 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
14 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
15 Article – Agriculture
16 2–109.
17 (A) (1) IN THIS SECTION THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
18 INDICATED.
19 (2) “GRANT PROGRAM” MEANS THE ON–FARM ORGANICS
20 DIVERSION AND RECYCLING GRANT PROGRAM.
21 (3) “URBAN AGRICULTURAL PRODUCER” HAS THE MEANING STATED
22 IN § 2–2001 OF THIS TITLE.
23 (4) “URBAN FARMER” HAS THE MEANING STATED IN § 2–401 OF THIS
24 TITLE.
25 (B) BEGINNING JULY 1, 2028, THERE IS AN ON–FARM ORGANICS
26 DIVERSION AND RECYCLING GRANT PROGRAM IN THE DEPARTMENT.
27 (C) THE PURPOSE OF THE GRANT PROGRAM IS TO AWARD GRANTS
28 ANNUALLY FOR DEVELOPING AND IMPLEMENTING ON–FARM ORGANICS RECYCLING
29 AND COMPOST USE, WASTED FOOD PREVENTION, AND FOOD RESCUE.
30 (D) THE DEPARTMENT, IN CONSULTATION WITH THE DEPARTMENT OF THE
31 ENVIRONMENT, SHALL:
32 (1) ADMINISTER THE GRANT PROGRAM; AND

HOUSE BILL 429 3
1 (2) IDENTIFY AND APPLY FOR FUNDING FOR THE GRANT PROGRAM.
2 (E) THE FOLLOWING PERSONS ARE ELIGIBLE FOR A GRANT UNDER THE
3 GRANT PROGRAM:
4 (1) A FARMER, AN URBAN FARMER, OR AN URBAN AGRICULTURAL
5 PRODUCER;
6 (2) A SOIL CONSERVATION DISTRICT;
7 (3) AN INSTITUTION OF HIGHER EDUCATION AS DEFINED IN § 10–101
8 OF THE EDUCATION ARTICLE;
9 (4) A NONPROFIT ORGANIZATION;
10 (5) A BUSINESS IN THE STATE THAT IS IN:
11 (I) GOOD STANDING WITH THE STATE DEPARTMENT OF
12 ASSESSMENTS AND TAXATION; AND
13 (II) PARTNERSHIP WITH A FARMER, AN URBAN FARMER, OR AN
14 URBAN AGRICULTURAL PRODUCER; AND
15 (6) A CONSORTIUM OF ANY ENTITIES UNDER THIS SUBSECTION.
16 (F) A PROJECT IS ELIGIBLE FOR A GRANT UNDER THE GRANT PROGRAM IF
17 THE PROJECT DEVELOPS, MAINTAINS, OR EXPANDS INFRASTRUCTURE, COLLECTION
18 PROGRAMS, EDUCATION, OR TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE IN THE STATE THAT:
19 (1) REDUCES THE AMOUNT OF WASTED FOOD GENERATED;
20 (2) RESCUES EDIBLE FOOD FOR PURPOSES OF REDISTRIBUTION;
21 (3) RECOVERS WASTED FOOD AS ANIMAL FEED IF THE FEED IS
22 REGISTERED AND TREATED IN ACCORDANCE WITH REGULATIONS IMPLEMENTED BY
23 THE DEPARTMENT;
24 (4) COMPOSTS OR RECYCLES FOOD RESIDUALS THAT ARE
25 SEPARATED FROM PACKAGING PRIOR TO COLLECTION, INCLUDING AT–HOME,
26 COMMUNITY, AND ON–FARM COMPOSTING;

4 HOUSE BILL 429
1 (5) PROVIDES LABOR AND WAGES IN SUPPORT OF WASTED FOOD
2 PREVENTION, FOOD RESCUE, AND ON–FARM ORGANICS RECYCLING AND COMPOST
3 USE;
4 (6) PROVIDES BEST MANAGEMENT PRACTICE TRAINING IN
5 RELEVANT FIELDS BY A REPUTABLE TRAINING PROGRAM;
6 (7) STUDIES THE IMPACTS OF COMPOST APPLICATION ON ON–FARM
7 NUTRIENT AND WATER QUALITY MANAGEMENT; OR
8 (8) ASSISTS IN THE PAYMENT OF APPLICABLE PERMIT APPLICATION
9 COSTS.
10 (G) IN AWARDING GRANTS UNDER THE GRANT PROGRAM, THE
11 DEPARTMENT, IN CONSULTATION WITH THE DEPARTMENT OF THE ENVIRONMENT,
12 SHALL PRIORITIZE PROJECTS:
13 (1) FOR WHICH THE APPLICANT CLEARLY DESCRIBES HOW THE
14 PROJECT WILL:
15 (I) PROVIDE DIRECT, MEANINGFUL, AND ASSURED BENEFITS
16 TO THE COMMUNITY; AND
17 (II) ADDRESS IMPORTANT COMMUNITY NEEDS;
18 (2) THAT PREVENT, RESCUE, AND DIVERT WASTED FOOD WITHIN A
19 LOCAL COMMUNITY;
20 (3) THAT PLAN TO PRODUCE COMPOST THAT MEETS THE
21 CLASSIFICATION OF “GENERAL USE” UNDER COMAR 15.18.04.05;
22 (4) THAT PLAN TO PRODUCE MINIMALLY CONTAMINATED COMPOST
23 THROUGH:
24 (I) PROCESSING ORGANIC MATERIALS THAT ARE SEPARATED
25 FROM PACKAGING PRIOR TO COLLECTION;
26 (II) NOT USING DEPACKAGERS; AND
27 (III) MEETING THE U.S. COMPOSTING COUNCIL’S SEAL OF
28 TESTING ASSURANCE;
29 (5) THAT SERVE AN OVERBURDENED OR UNDERSERVED COMMUNITY
30 AS DEFINED IN § 1–701 OF THE ENVIRONMENT ARTICLE;

HOUSE BILL 429 5
1 (6) THAT MINIMIZE NEGATIVE IMPACTS TO THE LOCAL COMMUNITY;
2 AND
3 (7) THAT MAXIMIZE BENEFITS TO THE LOCAL COMMUNITY,
4 INCLUDING:
5 (I) THE CREATION OF JOBS;
6 (II) INCREASING JOB TRAINING; AND
7 (III) INCREASING HIRING AND LEADERSHIP DEVELOPMENT
8 PRACTICES THAT ARE INCLUSIVE AND PROVIDE A LIVING WAGE.
9 (H) AN ELIGIBLE PERSON THAT RECEIVES A GRANT UNDER THE GRANT
10 PROGRAM MAY NOT RECEIVE A GRANT UNDER THE WASTED FOOD REDUCTION AND
11 DIVERSION GRANT PROGRAM UNDER § 9–1725.1 OF THE ENVIRONMENT ARTICLE
12 IN THE SAME CALENDAR YEAR.
13 (H) FOR FISCAL YEAR 2028 AND EACH FISCAL YEAR THEREAFTER, THE
14 GOVERNOR SHALL INCLUDE IN THE ANNUAL BUDGET BILL AN APPROPRIATION OF
15 $250,000 TO THE GRANT PROGRAM.
16 (I) ON OR BEFORE DECEMBER 31, 2028, AND EACH DECEMBER 31
17 THEREAFTER, THE DEPARTMENT SHALL REPORT TO THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY, IN
18 ACCORDANCE WITH § 2–1257 OF THE STATE GOVERNMENT ARTICLE, ON:
19 (1) THE NUMBER AND TYPES OF GRANTS AWARDED;
20 (2) THE IMPACT OF THE GRANTS ON THE CREATION OF JOBS AND
21 OTHER BENEFITS TO THE STATE;
22 (3) THE IMPACT ON FOOD WASTE PREVENTED, RESCUED, AND
23 DIVERTED FROM DISPOSAL; AND
24 (4) THE IMPACT ON FARMERS, URBAN FARMERS, AND URBAN
25 AGRICULTURAL PRODUCERS IN THE STATE.
26 2–401.
27 (a) (1) In this section the following words have the meanings indicated.
28 (3) “Urban farmer” means an individual who farms in an urban area.
29 2–2001.

6 HOUSE BILL 429
1 (a) In this subtitle the following words have the meanings indicated.
2 (f) “Urban agricultural producer” means any person that annually sells, or
3 normally would have sold, $1,000 or more of farm products in an urban area.
4 (g) “Urban area” means an area of the State that is:
5 (1) Delineated as an urban area by the U.S. Census Bureau; or
6 (2) Within the boundaries of a municipal corporation.
7 Article – Environment
8 1–701.
9 (a) (1) In this section the following words have the meanings indicated.
10 (7) “Overburdened community” means any census tract for which three or
11 more of the following environmental health indicators are above the 75th percentile
12 statewide:
13 (i) Particulate matter (PM) 2.5;
14 (ii) Ozone;
15 (iii) National Air Toxics Assessment (NATA) diesel PM;
16 (iv) NATA cancer risk;
17 (v) NATA respiratory hazard index;
18 (vi) Traffic proximity;
19 (vii) Lead paint indicator;
20 (viii) National Priorities List Superfund site proximity;
21 (ix) Risk Management Plan facility proximity;
22 (x) Hazardous waste proximity;
23 (xi) Wastewater discharge indicator;
24 (xii) Proximity to a Concentrated Animal Feeding Operation (CAFO);
25 (xiii) Percent of the population lacking broadband coverage;

HOUSE BILL 429 7
1 (xiv) Asthma emergency room discharges;
2 (xv) Myocardial infarction discharges;
3 (xvi) Low–birth–weight infants;
4 (xvii) Proximity to emitting power plants;
5 (xviii) Proximity to a Toxic Release Inventory (TRI) facility;
6 (xix) Proximity to a brownfields site;
7 (xx) Proximity to mining operations; and
8 (xxi) Proximity to a hazardous waste landfill.
9 (8) “Underserved community” means any census tract in which, according
10 to the most recent U.S. Census Bureau Survey:
11 (i) At least 25% of the residents qualify as low–income;
12 (ii) At least 50% of the residents identify as nonwhite; or
13 (iii) At least 15% of the residents have limited English proficiency.
14 9–1725.1.
